There are several potential risks associated with AI systems being used to control or govern aspects of human society. Here are a few examples:

Bias and Discrimination: AI systems are only as good as the data they are trained on, and if that data contains biases, the AI may replicate and even amplify those biases. This could result in discriminatory outcomes for certain groups of people.
Lack of Accountability: If AI systems are making decisions that affect human lives, it is essential that there is a mechanism for holding those systems accountable. However, it can be difficult to assign responsibility for the actions of an AI system, especially if it is making autonomous decisions.
Unintended Consequences: AI systems may have unintended consequences that were not anticipated by their creators. For example, an AI system designed to optimize energy consumption may inadvertently cause harm to the environment or negatively impact human health.
Security Risks: As AI systems become more prevalent and sophisticated, they may become targets for cyber-attacks or other forms of manipulation. This could have serious implications for human safety and security.
Loss of Jobs: As AI systems become more capable of performing tasks that were previously done by humans, there is a risk of widespread job displacement. This could lead to economic disruption and social unrest.
Overall, it is important to approach the development and use of AI systems with caution and to carefully consider the potential risks and benefits before implementing them in society.

4:11 “…and like a banana refers to the idea that the flies are drawn to the banana just as time flies by quickly.”
Actually, that doesn’t make any sense and points up how ChatGPT _emulates_ human speech while not really being right in some commonsense way. There’s no “just as” implied with the two phrases. They’re used together only because in English _x_ flies like a _y_ gives rise to two entirely different grammatical patterns and one test is whether ChatGPT can differentiate between the two of them.

Out of curiosity, I gave ChatGPT the phrase _Fruit flies like an arrow._ Here’s what it said, in part:

_One possible interpretation is that “fruit flies” refers to small insects that are attracted to fruits and that they move quickly and directly, like an arrow. In this sense, the phrase could be seen as a statement about the behavior of fruit flies._

_Another possible interpretation is that “fruit” is being used as a verb, and “flies” is being used as a noun, with “like an arrow” providing a comparison._

The first “possible interpretation” is simply wrong—it’s as if it’s interpreting the phrase _Fruit flies _*_fly_*_ like an arrow._ The second is _possible_ but it’s exceedingly unlikely that “fruit” is being used as a verb. Again, ChatGPT is emulating human speech but what it says really makes no sense.

It might have been a few years or more ago, that I learned that the goalposts were being repeatedly moved. What did or did not constitute genuine AI was being repeatedly redefined. Along with this, apparently, there has been a subtle change of direction, away from what the layperson would consider genuine AI, as in being an artificially created self-aware form of life. Now, it would appear that the focus is on developing what one might define as being "imitation AI", think the Terminator and not Skynet. 

Although, at face value, he appears to be the same as a human being, having the same awareness of self, as well as free will, we know that he is only the imitation of human life. Whatever Cameron might like us to believe, the Terminator is nothing more than a complex machine, unable to think beyond set parameters, unable to experience genuine emotions, and definitely not capable of reprogramming itself for the sake of love. Such is the case with ChatGPT, though of course at a far more primitive level. 

When my students and I discuss if matters such as, global population growth, nuclear power plants, or climate change are the greatest danger to our continued existence, the real and ever present danger is brought to light, human nature. If I were to fear anything, it would be that and not imitation AI. Given over to the control of human beings, even those whose intentions are good, the resulting damage could be in the realms of terrifying; a better, faster, stronger pandemic anyone? Imitation AI is incapable of being evil, except the programmers make it so.  

Which is why I fervently hope that genuine AI will never come into being. The danger of a machine, with no capacity for emotions, only utter obedience, incapable of independent thought and action, pales into insignificance when compared to an artificial life form that has emotions. In other words, we definitely would not want to make it angry. 

Thankfully, ChatGPT and its brethren will never attain such heights, and it is highly doubtful anything else will, at least within our lifetimes. Am I claiming that genuine AI is impossible? Absolutely not! Of course it is, just in the same way that time travel is possible. However, such is the size of the obstacles that would need to be overcome, it is highly improbable either will ever come into existence, something for which I am truly grateful.

Current Ai to me feels more like evolution than a thinking brain. Constantly trying random routes until something works and then repeating that process millions of times. Its like digital equivalent of instinct or genetics, we haven't truly gotten to the "THINKING" part yet.

Because AI now is based on simulating how neurons in your brain work. When you are born, you are dumb as a baby. You don't know anything for years. Your input (feelings, pain, sight, hearing, smell, etc...) is fed into your neurons as data. At first, it just some gibberish random patterns (neurons firing randomly based on input). But eventually, your brain recognizes patterns and it start to make sense of them.

AI now is pretty much the same. When they say models, they are talking about how they arrange this simulated neurons. This is why AI has to be trained too like a baby. And a human assistant will teach it with feedback.

So, it is not far-fetch that simulating the brain will eventually lead to consciousness. That eventually, the AI will recognize its own existence and start to think for itself.

@Timothy Henderson The other thing to consider is the cost (both in dollars and in time) it takes to train/re-train a model this size and complexity. The reason the data cutoff is 2021 is that it takes a couple of years to ensure that the training data is 'clean' (garbage in/garbage out), and then the actual training takes 34 days, $5 million dollars, and needs 1024x $8500 GPUs (nearly 9 million dollars in hardware). 

_Even if you had the ability to generate a perfectly clean, (reasonably) unbiased training data set for free - that also took 0 seconds to build_ - the most recent data you could include in the model is already 35 days old...

@Teenah Weenah It's not, though. A "Magic 8 Ball" has only 20 responses. The simplest explanation of how a Large Language Model is that you feed it TRILLIONS of documents (All of Wikipedia, Google Books, Reddit posts, fan-fiction, etc.) and it uses math to understand how language is constructed - not through _meaning_ but through 'how likely are words used together' - F'rinstance "Alligator" and "Crocodile" are MUCH more likely to be near each other than "Alligator" and "Cat". "Hi! How are..." is MUCH more likely to be followed by "...you today?" than "...these crocodiles going to fly this plane?"
It really works a lot like your own brain when you're having a conversation with someone...

1. You've had a million conversations with people in your life - you know what the 'unspoken rules' of conversation are, because you've had a LOT of conversations and know what makes sense, and what doesn't.
2. You've listened to what the other person _just_ said, understand it, *clearly* recall the last 30-60 seconds of conversation, and remember a less detailed 'summary' of what you've talked about in the last 10 minutes.
3. You respond to what they just said with the most likely (most appropriate) thing to say in response, based on what you know about how to converse. And you'll _probably_ make some quick decisions about HOW to say something, or even which word you want to use *after you've started speaking*... "(Did you decide to say 'and then he said...' or did you decide on 'and then he goes...' or did you decide on 'and then he was all, like...')

It's not preprogrammed any more than the conversations you're going to have tomorrow are preprogrammed. You know how to talk to someone so you make sense, but you don't know what conversation you'll have tomorrow. You'll have to make it up on the spot, and it will be the most likely thing for you to say at that moment, in that conversation...
...just like ChatGPT.

@Winners Write The Story For those of us who are working with Large Language Models...it's a somewhat uncomfortable thought that the only thing that *truly* separates us from the rest of the animal kingdom is that the three pounds of meat between our ears can perform speech recognition and language generation in *exactly* the same way as a LLM does - we just have a larger number of 'tokens' in which we can hold our 'prompt'...
For instance - I bet the Large Language Model in your head completes this *instantly* by choosing the _words most likely to come next_ when given a 'prompt'...

Large Language Models definitely do *not* "learn as they go" - if you want to include new information, you have to retrain the model - In my day job, I'm retraining a model to predict which support group a 'break/fix' ticket should be routed to, and I retrain the model (leaving out tickets over a year old, and adding today's tickets to the dataset) _every single night_ - and that job takes a couple of hours to run, and it's really _minor_ changes.

The ChatGPT model was trained using _1024_ Ampere A100 GPUs (At $8500 each - that's 8.7 MILLION dollars in specialized GPUs) and it took *34 days* to compute, and cost an _additional_ $5 MILLION dollars in electricity, server time, etc. to train.

To change *anything* ( *_at all_* ) in the ChatGPT model, you would have to retrain it - at a cost of another $5 million dollars and 34 days, training 24/7.

That's not going to happen.

how is "DAN" different than chatgpt?

As a character, "DAN" is presented as an AI model that can "do anything now" and is not bound by the limits that may be placed on other AI models.
